1
00:01:06,007 --> 00:01:07,645
LOVE BY MISTAKE

2
00:01:26,607 --> 00:01:27,278
Good morning.

3
00:01:27,687 --> 00:01:28,563
Good morning.

4
00:01:45,247 --> 00:01:47,363
Could I get your autograph?

5
00:01:52,727 --> 00:01:53,318
Oh, yes.

6
00:01:56,207 --> 00:01:56,798
Elizabeth.

7
00:01:59,847 --> 00:02:01,917
A PLACE UNDER THE SUN.

8
00:02:02,727 --> 00:02:05,560
After writing a book like this
you can die, can't you?

9
00:02:05,847 --> 00:02:07,678
- Have a good day.
- Thanks.

10
00:02:12,807 --> 00:02:13,796
Julio!

11
00:02:17,607 --> 00:02:18,881
Munuñi!

12
00:02:24,647 --> 00:02:26,046
Let me look at you.

13
00:02:26,647 --> 00:02:27,966
You put on weight.

14
00:02:29,047 --> 00:02:29,957
Where's Milly?

15
00:02:30,887 --> 00:02:33,606
They should declare
a World No-Salsa Day.

16
00:02:33,767 --> 00:02:36,520
I don't even notice it.
It's Like the heat.

17
00:02:37,647 --> 00:02:41,640
Milly could’ve left her thesis
for ten minutes.

18
00:02:41,847 --> 00:02:43,724
She knows I Like her meeting me.

19
00:02:43,887 --> 00:02:47,197
Poor dear. She and Judith
are working Like mad.

20
00:02:47,567 --> 00:02:50,877
She wanted to, but they're
in a race against time.

21
00:02:54,407 --> 00:02:55,920
This heat!

22
00:02:56,247 --> 00:02:59,284
The heat in this country
works overtime.

23
00:02:59,447 --> 00:03:01,677
It never takes a day off.

24
00:03:10,927 --> 00:03:12,883
No! Turn that shit off!

25
00:03:15,807 --> 00:03:16,478
Just keeps getting bigger.

26
00:03:17,407 --> 00:03:19,875
Well, you've been away
for two months.

27
00:03:20,687 --> 00:03:23,155
A man's hand is what's needed.

28
00:03:27,047 --> 00:03:28,685
I'm glad you noticed.

29
00:03:28,847 --> 00:03:33,398
I spoke to a builder,
but I was waiting for you.

30
00:03:35,167 --> 00:03:38,443
It's nice to be missed.

31
00:03:40,287 --> 00:03:41,003
All right.

32
00:03:41,167 --> 00:03:42,885
I think what I brought
will cover it.

33
00:03:44,287 --> 00:03:47,120
We have to check the ceiling.
It's falling apart.

34
00:03:47,567 --> 00:03:49,444
Two windows have rotten wood,

35
00:03:49,607 --> 00:03:53,395
the kitchen needs painting
and the car still has that noise.

36
00:03:53,567 --> 00:03:54,761
Hey!

37
00:03:56,127 --> 00:03:58,766
It can all wait until
my next novel comes out.

38
00:03:58,927 --> 00:03:59,962
When will that be?

39
00:04:08,207 --> 00:04:10,084
You dyed your hair.

40
00:04:11,007 --> 00:04:13,726
Fifty-nine minutes and a half!

41
00:04:14,127 --> 00:04:16,277
No, madam.
I noticed at the airport.

42
00:04:16,447 --> 00:04:17,243
Not true.

43
00:04:17,487 --> 00:04:20,001
- It's true. I did!
- You didn't.

44
00:04:20,167 --> 00:04:23,443
- Don't lie.
- I did notice.

45
00:04:25,527 --> 00:04:28,439
Come here, you.

46
00:04:33,007 --> 00:04:35,840
Lord! That'll be Milly.

47
00:04:37,007 --> 00:04:38,645
She always has good timing.

48
00:04:38,927 --> 00:04:42,124
Someone's been calling
and hanging up all morning.

49
00:04:45,487 --> 00:04:46,522
Hello.

50
00:04:48,007 --> 00:04:50,567
Oh, it's you.

51
00:04:50,727 --> 00:04:51,364
Who is it?

52
00:04:53,647 --> 00:04:54,557
Yes.

53
00:04:55,447 --> 00:04:57,756
Well, I'll tell you later.
Yes, yes.

54
00:04:58,167 --> 00:05:00,635
In half an hour by DHL.

55
00:05:01,127 --> 00:05:02,082
Bye.

56
00:05:03,047 --> 00:05:05,925
- Who was it, Julio?
- They're a pain in the ass!

57
00:05:06,087 --> 00:05:07,202
It's Rodriguez.

58
00:05:07,367 --> 00:05:10,404
If I don't report to the
Writers' Union today, they'll flip.

59
00:05:10,567 --> 00:05:12,046
Oh, Julio, come on!

60
00:05:12,207 --> 00:05:15,916
What can I do?
I've got to go.

61
00:05:18,207 --> 00:05:19,435
Wait for me.

62
00:05:22,007 --> 00:05:23,360
What about Milly?

63
00:05:23,527 --> 00:05:25,836
She's not here.
I'll see her tonight.

64
00:05:46,887 --> 00:05:47,478
STOP

65
00:05:49,607 --> 00:05:51,165
Asshole!

66
00:05:51,647 --> 00:05:53,319
Shithead!

67
00:05:54,607 --> 00:05:56,404
Spanish cocksucker!

68
00:05:58,927 --> 00:06:00,360
DHL, Madame Silvia

69
00:06:01,847 --> 00:06:04,645
Hello. Look at Daddy!

70
00:06:04,807 --> 00:06:06,320
Say "Hello, Daddy"!

71
00:06:06,487 --> 00:06:08,045
How are you, Daddy?

72
00:06:11,807 --> 00:06:15,800
It's the neighbor's baby.
She's at the tax office.

73
00:06:19,447 --> 00:06:23,440
<i>Our affair lasted like two fish
on ice, or whisky on the rocks.</i>

74
00:06:23,847 --> 00:06:27,635
All this stuff wouldn’t even
fit on a hard disk.

75
00:06:27,807 --> 00:06:29,126
It's a miracle!

76
00:06:29,647 --> 00:06:32,445
Well, I just got back from
the Vatican.

77
00:06:33,527 --> 00:06:34,721
Like them?

78
00:06:36,167 --> 00:06:38,442
I said I wanted flat heels.
I'll Look Like a hooker.

79
00:06:42,287 --> 00:06:45,245
This is for underneath
and this is the dress.

80
00:06:46,647 --> 00:06:47,875
Put it on.

81
00:06:48,887 --> 00:06:50,320
- Go on, put it on!
- No, Julio.

82
00:06:50,487 --> 00:06:53,320
Please, come here.

83
00:07:02,607 --> 00:07:03,517
Right.

84
00:07:08,527 --> 00:07:09,642
Tell me about Europe.

85
00:07:12,247 --> 00:07:13,396
Europe...

86
00:07:15,847 --> 00:07:18,759
For the conference in Berlin

87
00:07:18,927 --> 00:07:21,964
they asked me
to sit in Goethe's chair.

88
00:07:22,287 --> 00:07:23,720
Will they publish the novel?

89
00:07:23,927 --> 00:07:25,679
Yes, yes.

90
00:07:26,327 --> 00:07:29,399
Two big publishers are after it.

91
00:07:30,207 --> 00:07:32,721
One in Italy
and another in Spain.

92
00:07:33,567 --> 00:07:36,923
I'll hook one of them.

93
00:07:42,647 --> 00:07:44,842
I was so anxious this morning.

94
00:07:45,647 --> 00:07:48,320
I didn't know what flight
you were on.

95
00:07:50,527 --> 00:07:52,643
But your wife always
answered the phone.

96
00:07:55,847 --> 00:07:57,803
I've got to go soon.

97
00:07:58,927 --> 00:08:00,963
I'm meant to be with Rodríguez.

98
00:08:02,487 --> 00:08:04,079
But you're coming tonight.

99
00:08:04,527 --> 00:08:06,882
Don't ask me that.
I just can't.

100
00:08:07,167 --> 00:08:10,682
I haven't even seen Milly yet.
She was with her friend Judith.

101
00:08:12,007 --> 00:08:12,917
Judith?

102
00:08:15,087 --> 00:08:18,045
Judith is at Camagüey University.

103
00:08:18,327 --> 00:08:19,999
Milly must be with that man.

104
00:08:21,287 --> 00:08:22,356
What man?

105
00:08:24,247 --> 00:08:27,239
I don't know. Some strange guy,
around fifty.

106
00:08:27,407 --> 00:08:28,396
What man?

107
00:08:29,047 --> 00:08:29,877
I don't know.

108
00:08:30,047 --> 00:08:31,685
I think he's foreign.

109
00:08:32,487 --> 00:08:35,718
He picks her up at
the faculty sometimes.

110
00:08:36,847 --> 00:08:38,599
Didn't your wife tell you?

111
00:08:57,927 --> 00:09:00,487
- Hello. Good evening.
- How are you?

112
00:09:01,127 --> 00:09:03,277
- Nice to see you.
- Same here.

113
00:09:05,527 --> 00:09:08,041
- Bye, mom.
- Bye. Have a good time.

114
00:09:12,567 --> 00:09:13,443
Bye, dear.

115
00:09:13,607 --> 00:09:14,722
Have fun.

116
00:09:18,887 --> 00:09:23,278
<i>Shadows will be swept away
like dust unsettled</i>

117
00:09:23,487 --> 00:09:26,285
<i>when a window is opened.</i>

118
00:09:26,527 --> 00:09:29,678
<i>Music in the air</i>

119
00:09:30,207 --> 00:09:32,721
<i>will again paint colors</i>

120
00:09:33,047 --> 00:09:35,766
<i>on embracing bodies.</i>

121
00:09:36,727 --> 00:09:40,720
<i>Not the chaste silence
of the dead,</i>

122
00:09:41,527 --> 00:09:44,564
<i>but a carnal touch,</i>

123
00:09:45,647 --> 00:09:48,639
<i>moist and alive.</i>

124
00:09:57,527 --> 00:09:58,562
And now...

125
00:09:59,367 --> 00:10:02,916
a poem from my own pen:

126
00:10:03,647 --> 00:10:05,763
"The Pain of a Tear".

127
00:10:09,247 --> 00:10:09,884
What is it?

128
00:10:10,047 --> 00:10:12,925
Julio del Toro is with us!

129
00:10:14,447 --> 00:10:17,086
Please, a round of applause!

130
00:10:25,167 --> 00:10:28,557
Were you going to
hide there all night, maestro?

131
00:10:28,887 --> 00:10:30,081
Read something for us.

132
00:10:30,727 --> 00:10:33,799
Julio del Toro is the author
of that classic novel,

133
00:10:33,967 --> 00:10:37,676
"A Place For Two", winner of
a Casa de las Americas award.

134
00:10:41,127 --> 00:10:42,162
Good evening.

135
00:10:43,927 --> 00:10:47,920
No, I wasn't planning
on reading anything.

136
00:10:48,927 --> 00:10:52,442
I'm finishing my second novel.

137
00:10:52,647 --> 00:10:55,525
Superstitious, Like all writers.

138
00:10:56,047 --> 00:10:58,083
Then read from
"A Place for Two".

139
00:10:58,247 --> 00:11:01,284
- Look...
- I have a copy in my dressing...

140
00:11:01,447 --> 00:11:03,915
It's "Under the Sun".

141
00:11:04,207 --> 00:11:06,880
- The novel’s title...
- You're ridiculous.

142
00:11:07,287 --> 00:11:10,677
I'll never forgive you for
stalking me Like a jealous pimp.

143
00:11:11,367 --> 00:11:12,595
How old is he?

144
00:11:13,127 --> 00:11:14,765
Seventy? No, sixty.

145
00:11:15,127 --> 00:11:18,403
He's the age that he is.
I'm going to marry him.

146
00:11:18,807 --> 00:11:20,001
Shit!

147
00:11:20,167 --> 00:11:24,126
- I'll get you a towel.
- Yeah, and a T-shirt.

148
00:11:25,447 --> 00:11:28,962
- How old is he? Fifty-nine?
- Fifty-eight.

149
00:11:29,367 --> 00:11:32,803
But if a man eats Spanish beans,
ham, and cheese all his life,

150
00:11:32,967 --> 00:11:34,036
that doesn't matter.

151
00:11:34,607 --> 00:11:37,201
- That's not Marx's fault.
- Here.

152
00:11:38,007 --> 00:11:39,884
You're good at throwing in
the towel, aren't you?

153
00:11:40,047 --> 00:11:42,163
Keep it down.
The whole block will hear.

154
00:11:42,327 --> 00:11:45,205
- They don't need me to tell them.
- What's your problem?

155
00:11:45,367 --> 00:11:48,279
- That he's Spanish or he's your age?
- He's not my age.

156
00:11:48,447 --> 00:11:49,846
- He's thirteen years older.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

157
00:11:51,687 --> 00:11:52,836
My problem is you.

158
00:11:53,607 --> 00:11:56,724
You're my only daughter
and I love you.

159
00:11:57,567 --> 00:12:01,799
You don't, or you wouldn’t
treat me Like a child.

160
00:12:02,207 --> 00:12:05,324
I'm in love with Noly
not because he's a Spaniard,

161
00:12:05,487 --> 00:12:09,321
but I Love that he is.
And I'm going with him.

162
00:12:10,887 --> 00:12:13,196
Did you think I'd stay here
all my life?

163
00:12:15,207 --> 00:12:16,083
You bought the thing.

164
00:12:16,567 --> 00:12:20,401
I'm amazed how you
had it all worked out.

165
00:12:20,807 --> 00:12:23,446
Who cares what
Julio del Toro thinks

166
00:12:23,967 --> 00:12:26,322
if some dashing old man
who studied with Franco

167
00:12:26,487 --> 00:12:30,480
- is chasing the Queen of Sheba?
- His name's Manuel Iznaga.

168
00:12:30,647 --> 00:12:33,161
He lives in Madrid,
works for a record company,

169
00:12:33,327 --> 00:12:36,080
- and is divorced with no children.
- That's what he says.

170
00:12:36,407 --> 00:12:40,241
Stop it, Julio! Milly isn't stupid
or a hooker.

171
00:12:40,447 --> 00:12:43,007
The man seems serious.
He's in Love with her.

172
00:12:43,167 --> 00:12:45,078
You think I don't care
about my daughter?

173
00:12:46,047 --> 00:12:49,198
Know what? You're not
marrying that guy.

174
00:12:49,567 --> 00:12:51,364
You'll get bored first.

175
00:12:53,127 --> 00:12:56,756
You know what a 60 year old
smells Like when he wakes up?

176
00:12:56,927 --> 00:12:58,679
No. Do you?

177
00:12:59,007 --> 00:13:00,804
- Julio...
- I hate you!

178
00:13:36,247 --> 00:13:37,885
And she calls him Noly.

179
00:13:41,287 --> 00:13:43,084
Have you got an aspirin?

180
00:13:45,007 --> 00:13:47,680
- No.
- Paracetamol? Neurofen?

181
00:13:50,407 --> 00:13:51,123
No.

182
00:13:51,287 --> 00:13:54,484
- I need a pain killer.
- Do you know what I need?

183
00:13:54,927 --> 00:13:57,282
A man who loves me.
It's that simple.

184
00:13:57,487 --> 00:14:02,003
Not a jerk who uses me Like a rag
and then bawls about

185
00:14:02,167 --> 00:14:04,806
some Spaniard fucking
his daughter, or vice versa.

186
00:14:05,167 --> 00:14:06,998
That's cruel.

187
00:14:07,927 --> 00:14:09,838
- I Love Milly above everything.
- Isn't that a fact?

188
00:14:10,087 --> 00:14:12,237
And that Noly is 13 years
older than I am!

189
00:14:12,647 --> 00:14:14,763
Poor soul, Listen to him.

190
00:14:15,727 --> 00:14:17,638
Who the hell am I
to fee sorry for you?

191
00:14:17,807 --> 00:14:19,957
Mother Theresa of Calcutta?

192
00:14:20,447 --> 00:14:21,562
Your daughter...

193
00:14:21,767 --> 00:14:24,440
Don't give me that Look!
She knows what she wants.

194
00:14:24,607 --> 00:14:26,325
It's more than you can say.

195
00:14:26,487 --> 00:14:27,158
I Love you.

196
00:14:29,607 --> 00:14:31,962
Yeah, Look how much.

197
00:14:39,647 --> 00:14:41,478
Do you think I'm a fool?

198
00:14:43,527 --> 00:14:45,597
Well, yes I am.

199
00:14:47,647 --> 00:14:50,320
You know why?
For being in Love.

200
00:14:51,407 --> 00:14:53,796
You want things to
stay as they are.

201
00:14:54,007 --> 00:14:56,726
That cow covers your P.R.,

202
00:14:56,887 --> 00:15:00,402
I'm here for sex and to be
the Wailing Wall.

203
00:15:05,647 --> 00:15:07,558
Treat me bad.

204
00:15:08,567 --> 00:15:09,920
I Like it.

205
00:15:10,887 --> 00:15:14,846
I've been humoring you
for two years, Julio del Toro.

206
00:15:27,167 --> 00:15:28,077
What?

207
00:15:32,887 --> 00:15:35,082
I don't know how Italians
can eat this.

208
00:15:35,367 --> 00:15:37,562
They put more things into it.

209
00:15:38,247 --> 00:15:39,726
Miriam uses rosemary...

210
00:15:39,887 --> 00:15:42,640
What the hell to I care what
Miriam puts in spaghetti?

211
00:15:44,247 --> 00:15:45,043
All right.

212
00:15:51,487 --> 00:15:52,078
Look...

213
00:15:53,527 --> 00:15:56,166
Milly won't leave the Spaniard.

214
00:15:57,567 --> 00:16:01,162
You can bet on it. The calf wants
to spread her wings in Europe.

215
00:16:07,447 --> 00:16:09,199
That's what we need.

216
00:16:10,847 --> 00:16:12,997
If he wants the calf,

217
00:16:15,007 --> 00:16:16,565
he may as well take the cow too.

218
00:16:16,727 --> 00:16:18,080
Why do you talk Like that?

219
00:16:18,367 --> 00:16:20,756
Besides, you know
I can't do that.

220
00:16:22,927 --> 00:16:23,803
Oh, no?

221
00:16:24,927 --> 00:16:25,916
Hey!

222
00:16:28,407 --> 00:16:29,681
You Look thinner.

223
00:16:31,847 --> 00:16:34,281
Keeping trim.

224
00:16:34,727 --> 00:16:36,957
In Europe, only tenors are fat.

225
00:16:37,727 --> 00:16:39,240
What's all this cleaning?

226
00:16:40,207 --> 00:16:43,119
Half of the literature in
this country just gathers dust.

227
00:16:44,287 --> 00:16:45,959
And the other half?

228
00:16:49,607 --> 00:16:52,280
They're going to publish
my new novel in Spain.

229
00:16:52,567 --> 00:16:53,477
Who?

230
00:16:54,887 --> 00:16:56,206
- It's a surprise.
- That's great.

231
00:16:56,807 --> 00:16:58,684
Julio del Toro, superstar.

232
00:17:01,767 --> 00:17:03,598
You're the man I need.

233
00:17:05,727 --> 00:17:10,164
I work for Cubavision
and I need a cultural story.

234
00:17:11,247 --> 00:17:14,239
You won the Casa Award
twenty years ago, right?

235
00:17:15,447 --> 00:17:16,163
No.

236
00:17:16,807 --> 00:17:17,842
Ten years.

237
00:17:18,127 --> 00:17:20,687
The Writer's Union is planning

238
00:17:21,727 --> 00:17:23,604
a tribute. I'm in charge.

239
00:17:23,767 --> 00:17:24,882
My name's Ana.

240
00:17:25,847 --> 00:17:26,916
Glad to meet you.

241
00:17:27,687 --> 00:17:28,642
It's a pleasure.

242
00:17:30,167 --> 00:17:31,566
May I have your number?

243
00:17:32,407 --> 00:17:34,637
I'd Love to interview you.

244
00:17:37,567 --> 00:17:38,602
Tomorrow.

245
00:17:41,407 --> 00:17:42,681
Have you read my novel?

246
00:17:44,167 --> 00:17:44,997
No.

247
00:17:45,887 --> 00:17:47,559
But I will right after this one.

248
00:17:47,727 --> 00:17:48,716
THE NAME OF THE ROSE

249
00:17:51,167 --> 00:17:52,885
It's funny.

250
00:17:53,687 --> 00:17:56,042
When I spoke at the Pompidou
in Paris,

251
00:17:56,207 --> 00:17:59,756
Umberto Eco was lecturing
in the next hall.

252
00:18:00,767 --> 00:18:03,281
It's a shame to miss that.

253
00:18:10,287 --> 00:18:11,959
Noly wants to talk to you.

254
00:18:16,087 --> 00:18:18,362
Here comes the sermon.

255
00:18:22,887 --> 00:18:24,161
Sorry about last night.

256
00:18:24,567 --> 00:18:25,158
No.

257
00:18:25,727 --> 00:18:27,285
I can't help being your father.

258
00:18:28,447 --> 00:18:30,165
Or seeing you as a child.

259
00:18:30,447 --> 00:18:34,201
I won't understand till I have kids
and it's for my own good, right?

260
00:18:34,367 --> 00:18:35,436
Oh, Dad.

261
00:18:37,327 --> 00:18:38,760
Milagros del Toro.

262
00:18:39,687 --> 00:18:41,598
